In .NET MAUI, use `Application.Current.RequestedTheme` and the `RequestedThemeChanged` event. To override, set `Application.Current.UserAppTheme`.

```csharp
// Read current system theme
AppTheme current = Application.Current.RequestedTheme; // Dark, Light, or Unspecified

// Subscribe to real-time changes
Application.Current.RequestedThemeChanged += (s, e) =>
{
    AppTheme newTheme = e.RequestedTheme;
    Debug.WriteLine($"Theme changed to {newTheme}");

    // Update UI on main thread
    MainThread.BeginInvokeOnMainThread(() =>
    {
        // e.g. swap resource dictionaries, refresh colors, etc.
    });
};

// Force a specific theme (overrides system setting)
Application.Current.UserAppTheme = AppTheme.Dark;

// Revert to following the system theme
Application.Current.UserAppTheme = AppTheme.Unspecified;
```

**XAML shorthand** — use `AppThemeBinding` so controls react automatically:

```xml
<Label Text="Hello"
       TextColor="{AppThemeBinding Light=Black, Dark=White}" />
```

**Key points:**

- `RequestedTheme` — read-only, reflects the OS setting.
- `UserAppTheme` — read/write, your app-level override. Set to `Unspecified` to follow the system again.
- `RequestedThemeChanged` fires whenever the **system** theme changes (not when you set `UserAppTheme`).
- `AppThemeBinding` in XAML reacts to both system and user-forced changes with no code-behind needed.
